summary: You know, I’m ready to accept the idea the symbiote wanted to leave Eddie because of cancer. There were other reasons leading to...
body:
You know, I’m ready to accept the idea the symbiote wanted to leave Eddie because of cancer. There were other reasons leading to it too, like Eddie often being inconsiderate of the symbiote’s feelings, trying to shift his violent tendencies on it. Add the symbiote finding out it was pregnant again, and was going to loose the child if staying with Eddie, I can imagine it trying to leave.

But.

But there’s a huge plot hole I just can’t get past.

The same issue suggests Eddie has already had cancer when he first bonded with the symbiote. And that had no effect on birthing Carnage. In fact, he says the cancer was helping him produce more adrenaline to feed the symbiote.

And maybe something shifted in his illness, maybe it’s because the symbiote’s new child is a product of cloned seeds that was implanted into it, but it never explained.

It would’ve worked if it didn’t try rewriting Eddie’s past (and doing a rather bad job of it). He could’ve developed tumor later on, and only then his and the symbiote’s issues with staying together would’ve started.

As it is, The Spectacular Spider-Man: The Hunger goes into a giant bin of wasted apportunities, and instead of enriching Venom’s backstory or providing character development, it does great at ruining it.

The Spectacular Spider-Man: The Hunger #5
